<title type="html"><![CDATA[How to convert back to NTSC]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1226&amp;p=61081#p61081"><![CDATA[
I'm bringing this back from the dead because I've been doing some maintenance on my consoles... I added composite output to my SMS III, converted my Atari 2600 to NTSC (the guide I used for composite video resulted in colors that were too saturated so I reverted to RF), and now I feel like making my NES output NTSC video again.<br /><br />I found a <a href="http://www.nesarchive.net/forum/index.php?topic=11434.0" class="postlink">page in (bad) portuguese</a> that explains the whole procedure. It shows exactly what traces have to be reconnected and says that you have to replace the crystal with a 21.47727 MHz one. Thing is I can't find this crystal anywhere, but I have a 3.579545 MHz one (the same kind I used to make my Atari NTSC). IIRC, the 21.47727 MHz are divided to achieve the 3.579545 used in NTSC video, right? Does this mean that somehow I can bypass the divider and use my 3.579545 crystal?<br /><br />Please hardware gurus, let me know if you think this is possible and how.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=95">tokumaru</a> — Thu May 06, 2010 6:11 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
